Introduction¶

This is part of the "communicating data findings" project for the udacity data analyst nanodegree.
This notebook contains the initial data exploration. See readme for more information.

The dataset explored in this analysis is the 2012 PISA data. This data is associated to two files. The main data (pisa2012.csv) and a dictionary (pisadict2012.csv) for all the columns. Since the pisa data is quite large, I manually added a collumn to the dictionary file which indicates the columns I thought might be of interest.

The focus of this analysis will be to look at gender differences in academic achievement and look at interactions with subjective sense of belonging.

I will look at gaps in achievement between the two genders by country and then use correlations to guide further analysis.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The pisa data contains 485490 rows indicating unique students and 636 columns of information. Prior to the analysis I manaually selected 96 columns in the dictionary.

The columns included fall into the following categories

  1. demographic information.
  2. the level 5 maths, reading and science scores.
  3. the summary columns for questionairs.
  4. the full questionaire information for:
    1. "sense of belonging"
    2. "attitude towards school"
    3. "percieved control"
    4. "perseverence"

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

  1. Gender (ST04Q01)
  2. Math, Reading and Science scores (PV5MATH,PV5READ,PV5SCI)

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think Wealth and feature relating to social well being will be of interest, but my aim is to let the data speak for itself, by using correlations. Because of this approach I do not know in advance what features will be important for my investigation, and I might add features throughout the analysis.

Mathanxiety and other Math related features correlated with gender¶

After finding features that have at least a 0.1 correlation with gender we can observe a few interesting things that may be worth looking more closely into. While a correlation of 0.1 is quite low, we generally would not expect to see very high associations with gender gloabally.
As our questions become more specific we would expect correlations to also go up.

Mathanxiety (ANXMAT) is slightly negatively corrlated with the P5MATH scores (-0.36), and being female is weakly correlated with mathanxiety (-0.12). Therefore we might expect women to perform worse on maths tests. We do find a very very slight negative correlation (0.05) between being female and the PV5MATH. However this is the global data, and it is liekly that we will find stronger relationships with mathanxiety if we were too break down the relationship by country and culture.

Interestingly Mathanxiety was also associated with reading (-25) and science (-0.3) scores. It might be that mathanxiety is a good proxy for general feelings of anxiety and underperformance.

We also find correlations with MATHBEH (math behaviour), MATHEFF (self eficacy), MATHINTFC (intentions) and SCMAT (math self concept). All of these show a trend in favour of male students.
EXPUREM (experience with pure mathematics at school) was the only math related feature that was correlated positive with female students.

Gender and Reading + Science¶

We do not find a difference due to gender in the Science exam (PV5SCIE), but we do find a positive correlation between gender and reading ability PV5READ.

Gender and Teachers¶

Teacher behaviour is capturued in two featues these are TCHBEHFA (Formative assesment) and TCHBEHSO (student orientation). Both were negatively correlated with being female.

Tech and Gender¶

ENTUSE (ICT entertainment) is positeviely correlated with being male. (ICT = information and comunication technology)

Questions to think about:¶

1: Are Maths gender differences constant across countries? 2: Are Reading gender difference constant across countries? 3: Why is there a reading gap between male and female students? 4: What is reading score correlated with?

In [99]:
#calculate mean score for men, mean score for women, and difference. 
#df_mean_diff_maths= pa
df_gm_mean = df_pisa_full[["PV5MATH","PV5READ","PV5SCIE","ST04Q01","NC"]].groupby(by=["NC","ST04Q01"]).mean().reset_index()
#pivot to have seperate gender columns
df_gm_math_diff=df_gm_mean.pivot(index="NC",columns='ST04Q01', values=["PV5MATH","PV5READ","PV5SCIE"])
#calculate mean score across subjects for each country. (Row mean)
df_gm_math_diff["Mean_score"]= df_gm_math_diff.mean(axis=1)
#assign ranks based on mean score
df_gm_math_diff["Mean_score_rank"]= df_gm_math_diff.Mean_score.rank(ascending =False)
#loop through all 3 categories
for i_col in ["PV5MATH","PV5READ","PV5SCIE"]:
    #for each category mean male - mean female
    df_gm_math_diff[i_col+'_gdiff']=df_gm_math_diff[i_col]["Male"]-df_gm_math_diff[i_col]["Female"]

Maths¶

We can see higher average maths scores for female students in Jordan, Qatar, Thailand, Malaysia, Singapore, UAE, Iceland etc.

  1. Do girls have less math anxiety in these countries?
  2. What is the difference between countries were girls outperform boys in maths?
Reading¶

We can see that female students do better in reading in every single country since all values are negative.

Science¶

We can see that even though male and female students perform similairy in science globally, there are local differences. For example male students outperform women in Lichtenstein, Colombia, Costa Rica, Luxenbourh, Japan, UK etc. But female students outperform in Jordan, Qatar, the UAE etc.

  1. Why do women seem to outperform male students by such a high rate in all subjects in Jordan and Qatar?

In the case of Jordan, it seems like there is a well documented achievement gap in favour of female students. https://www.researchgate.net/publication/281280418_Gender_Gap_in_Student_Achievement_in_Jordan_Study_Report

Gender differences in Jordan:¶

Neagative correlation between being male and Math, Reading and Science scores.

Male students also have negative correlation with Attitude towards school (ATSCHL & ATTLNACT).

Sense of belonging (BELONG) is negatively correlated with male students.

They have more availablity of computers at school and at home ('ICTHOME', 'ICTSCH',) but also see the computer as less helpful for learning ('ICTATTNEG'), use of computer at school is also positively correlated with being male. ('USESCH')

Mathematics behaviour is positevely correlated with being male, as is teacher behvariour towards formative assements.

Sense of Belonging Question broken down by gender in Jordan:¶

In [48]:
#get columns to plot
x_val_list=df_jordan.loc[:,"ST87Q01":"ST87Q09"].columns
n=len(x_val_list)

#define category order
cat_order= ['Strongly disagree', 'Disagree','Agree','Strongly agree']
plt.figure(figsize = [20,20 ])

for i in range(n):
    #make temp var
    temp_var=x_val_list[i]
    #get variable definition from temp variable
    var_def = df_pdic.loc[df_pdic.column_names == temp_var,"definition"].to_list()
    #make temp df that contains protoprition value counts
    temp_df=df_jordan.groupby(gender)[temp_var].value_counts(normalize=True).rename("Proportion").reset_index()
    plt.subplot(3,3,i+1)
    plt.subplots_adjust(hspace = .3)
    sns.barplot(x=temp_var,y="Proportion",data=temp_df,color = base_color,hue=gender,order=cat_order)
    plt.legend(title='Gender')
    plt.xlabel(var_def[0])
    plt.ylabel("Proportion broken down by gender")

Male students in Jordan were more liekly to feel like an outsider, and feel akward and feel lonely at school. Despite this males were more liekly to agree strongly that "things are ideal at school"
